20 Teves 5782 &ldquo;Moses took the staff of G‑d in his hand.&rdquo; (Shemos 4:20)
The Rebbe explains this verse in Chassidus, &ldquo;Even though Moshe gave Pharaoh the honor due a king and spoke to him respectfully, he made no compromises in his demands concerning the people&rsquo;s spiritual and physical needs. He spoke with &lsquo;the staff of G‑d in his hand,&rsquo; i.e., with authority and determination.&rdquo;
&ldquo;They will perish, but You will endure; all of them will wear out like a garment; You will exchange them like a robe, and they will vanish.

4 Teves 5782 &ldquo;And Israel said, &lsquo;Enough! My son Joseph is still alive. I will go and see him before I die.'&rdquo;
We all have those moments in our lives when we say &ldquo;Enough! Enough sadness, suffering and self-pity, it&rsquo;s time to act now. It&rsquo;s time to rebel against the spirit of indifference. Life is so beautiful. Hashem&rsquo;s Torah is so beautiful. I want to live by it!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Through the knowledge and comprehension of Torah by the soul of a person who studies it well, with the concentration of his intellect, to the point where the Torah is grasped by his mind and is joined with him so that they become one, [the Torah thereby] becomes food for the soul.

19 Kislev 5782 &ldquo;The pit was empty of water.&rdquo; (Bereishis 37:24)
&ldquo;Allegorically, the pit represents the human mind and water represents the Torah. This incident thus tells us that the surest way to keep our mind free of &lsquo;snakes and scorpions&rsquo; – negative and destructive notions – is to ensure that it is always full of Torah-related content, for &lsquo;G‑d’s Torah is wholesome, restoring the soul.'&rdquo;
&ldquo;He [the Alter Rebbe] sat at the seat of wisdom with our lord, master, and teacher, the world gaon [the Maggid of Mezritch] and he drew water from the well of living waters.
